i, input_dtype)\n   441→                parts.append(f\"{label}({original_vi}→{vi}, max={max_vo})\")\n   442→            else:\n   443→                label = get_lmul_label(vi, input_dtype)\n   444→                parts.append(f\"{label}({vi}, max={max_vo})\")\n   445→        probe_line = \"# Probe: \" + \" | \".join(parts)\n   446→        return line1 + '\\n' + probe_line\n   447→\n   448→    return line1\n   449→\n   450→\n   451→class DistVectorStrategy(TilingStrategy):\n   452→    \"\"\"Distribution-first tiling: distribution tiles → vector tiles.\n   453→\n   454→    Decision order:\n   455→    distribution(divisor-snapped) → LMUL tier → V_outer → K_peel"}]},"uuid":"31baf9a5-aba9-4179-a951-1e49b4f5ff69","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:05.992Z"},"type":"agent_progress","prompt":"","agentId":"a8ddd474f8dda762a"},"toolUseID":"agent_msg_01KTMWet1JMio5kf8oDY87bs","parentToolUseID":"toolu_01WvKHvxmXK9T5pdyr67cNsK","uuid":"d767e88e-4d98-4b0d-a885-a238437f9d22","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:05.994Z"}
{"parentUuid":"0a823226-b55e-4fdc-963b-3291682d970a","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/nick/work/ai_iree","sessionId":"71dec615-7b07-4e9a-9c31-50ec143dbbf8","version":"2.1.72","gitBranch":"master","slug":"purrfect-wandering-puppy","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WvKHvxmXK9T5pdyr67cNsK","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me create a comprehensive report.\n\n## Research Report: Search Space Configs with L3 Vec_parallel M=0\n\nI've thoroughly researched the codebase and found clear answers to all three questions. Here's what I discovered:\n\n### 1. **How configs like `[0, 64, 0]` in L3 are generated**\n\nThe M=0 (outer dimension) in L3 (vec_parallel level) comes from the `compute_v_outer_candidates()` function in `/home/nick/work/ai_iree/script/dataset_generator/search_space.py` (line 281).\n\n**Process:**\n- The distribution level (L0/L1) provides `dist_outer` and `dist_inner` values\n- For each LMUL tier `(v_inner, v_outer_max)`, the code calls `compute_v_outer_candidates(max_vo, dist_outer)` at line 331 in `strategy_dist_vector.py`\n- When filters eliminate all valid v_outer candidates, the function returns `[0]` as a fallback (line 328 in search_space.py)\n- This `[0]` is then assigned to L3[second_inner] at line 340 in strategy_dist_vector.py\n- The resulting config looks like `[[dist_outer, dist_inner], [dist_outer, dist_inner], [0...], [v_inner, 0, ...], ...]` for 6-level ops\n\n**Why M=0 occurs:**\n- Parity filtering eliminates candidates that don't match dim_M's parity (line 320 in search_space.py)\n- Other filters (V_OUTER_EXCLUDE, V_OUTER_MIN) can also eliminate all candidates\n- When all candidates are filtered out, the fallback returns `[0]`\n\n### 2. **The Probe mechanism**\n\nThe \"Probe\" shown in search space file comments represents **per-distribution-pair spill boundary probing**. Example from the code:\n```\n# Probe: MF4(32, max=4) | MF2(64, max=1) | LMUL1(128, max=0)\n```\n\n**What it is:**\n- `probe_fn` is a callable created by `make_dist_probe_fn()` at line 1611 in compiler.py\n- It's invoked **per-distribution-pair** (dist_outer, dist_inner) to determine the maximum non-spilling `v_outer` for each LMUL tier\n- Returns a dict: `{v_inner: max_v_outer}` where max_v_outer is the largest v_outer that doesn't cause register spills\n\n**How it works:**\n1. For each LMUL tier (MF4, MF2, LMUL1, etc.), it compiles a probe MLIR file with that v_inner/v_outer combination\n2. Uses binary search (at line 1572-1577 in compiler.py) to find the maximum v_outer where `v_outer=1` doesn't spill\n3. The result is stored in `dist_spill_bounds` at line 292 in strategy_dist_vector.py\n4. This bounds dict then constrains the v_outer candidates generated for that distribution tile\n\n**Caching:**\n- Results are cached in `ProbeCache` keyed by `(template_hash, dist_outer, dist_inner)` to avoid re-probing identical distribution pairs\n\n### 3. **What \"max=0\" means**\n\nIn the probe header comment, `max=0` means **\"V_outer=1 spills for this LMUL tier\"**.\n\n**Semantics:**\n- `max_v_outer` is the largest non-spilling v_outer value returned by the probe\n- `max=0` specifically means: **even V_outer=1 spills**, so this tier cannot be used for this distribution pair\n- Line 1528 in compiler.py sets `bounds[v_inner] = 0` when `initial_spill > 0` (V_outer=1 spills)\n- Line 325-327 in strategy_dist_vector.py then skips this tier:\n  ```python\n  max_vo = min(max_vo, dist_spill_bounds.get(v_inner, 0))\n  if max_vo == 0:\n      continue\n  ```\n- When all tiers are skipped, `compute_v_outer_candidates` returns `[0]`, which propagates to L3\n\n**Example trace for `[0, 64, 0]`:**\n- Distribution pair: (dist_outer=64, dist_inner=64)\n- Probe results: `{32: 0, 64: 0, 128: 0}` (all tiers spill at V_outer=1)\n- All tiers skipped in line 326-327\n- No v_outer candidates generated\n- compute_v_outer_candidates returns `[0]` (line 328)\n- L3[M_dim] becomes 0\n\n---\n\n**Files involved:**\n- `/home/nick/work/ai_iree/script/dataset_generator/search_space.py` - compute_v_outer_candidates, divisibility filters\n- `/home/nick/work/ai_iree/script/dataset_generator/strategy_dist_vector.py` - per-dist-pair probe invocation, format_dist_group_header\n- `/home/nick/work/ai_iree/script/dataset_generator/compiler.py` - probe_spill_bounds, binary search logic, ProbeCache"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a8ddd474f8dda762a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 62101\ntool_uses: 26\nduration_ms: 58498</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"c533d0bc-3071-4ae1-96f1-81ac7bc2481f","timestamp":"2026-03-20T02:58:20.458Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"In the codebase at /home/nick/work/ai_iree, find how the search space configs with L3 vec_parallel tile having M=0 are generated. Look in script/dataset_generator/search_space.py for how probe configs are created, specifically for the case where the M (outer) vec_parallel tile is 0. I need to understand:\n1. What generates configs like `[0, 64, 0]` in L3 \n2. What is the `Probe` mechanism shown in the search space file comments (e.g., \"Probe: MF4(32, max=4) | MF2(64, max=1) | LMUL1(128, max=0)\")\n3. What does \"max=0\" mean in this context\n\nJust research and report back, don't modify any files.","agentId":"a8ddd474f8dda762a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information I need. Let me create a comprehensive report.\n\n## Research Report: Search Space Configs with L3 Vec_parallel M=0\n\nI've thoroughly researched the codebase and found clear answers to all three questions. Here's what I discovered:\n\n### 1. **How configs like `[0, 64, 0]` in L3 are generated**\n\nThe M=0 (outer dimension) in L3 (vec_parallel level) comes from the `compute_v_outer_candidates()` function in `/home/nick/work/ai_iree/script/dataset_generator/search_space.py` (line 281).\n\n**Process:**\n- The distribu